A TEACHER who was allegedly beaten by a colleague in front of pupils wants the department of education to take action against her attacker. Andile Nene (25) from Silethukukhanya High School in Mtubatuba, northern KZN, claimed toDaily Sun a fellow teacher beat her on the head with a broomstick on Thursday. She claimed the fight started when the other teacher refused to move out of the way for her to enter the staff room. &ldquo;There wasn&rsquo;t a lot of space in the doorway but she started shouting at me for touching her as I entered the room. I politely apologised to her,&rdquo; she said.Andile said she prepared her lessons in the staff room, not knowing her colleague was waiting for her outside. &ldquo;When I left the room she asked me why I undermined her and picked up a steel broomstick. She started beating me, but I took the broom from her,&rdquo; Andile claimed. She said she ran to the principal&rsquo;s office because she was bleeding and pupils were laughing.They called the police from the office and Anele and her colleague were taken to the cop shop to give statements. &ldquo;What irritates me is that she thinks she can just pay me to withdraw the case. She begged me to name my price and not open a case,&rdquo; she said. SGB chairman Siya Khumalo said: &ldquo;We were shocked by the incident, but the matter was reported to the district office.&rdquo; Education department spokesman Sihle Mlotshwa said: &ldquo;We are not aware of the incident. We condemn such behaviour in the strongest possible terms.&rdquo; Police spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Thulani Zwane confirmed that a case of assault with intent to cause grievous bodily harm was opened at Mtubatuba cop shop.